WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:18.680
Hi, my name's Mark, I'm the founder of the R4Pi project and I'm really excited to speak

00:00:18.680 --> 00:00:27.020
to you about it today. I hope you're enjoying the conference so far. The R4Pi project exists

00:00:27.020 --> 00:00:33.380
to make it easier to run R on the Raspberry Pi family of computers. It's been possible

00:00:33.380 --> 00:00:38.099
to run R on them for a really, really long time, but the experience is not necessarily

00:00:38.099 --> 00:00:44.180
always a smooth one. So the R4Pi project really aims to kind of smooth that process out to

00:00:44.180 --> 00:00:50.459
make it a lot easier for folks to get started. We've got full documentation over at r4pi.org

00:00:50.459 --> 00:00:57.099
and I'm going to show you some more information about the project today.

00:00:57.099 --> 00:01:04.099
So what is a Raspberry Pi? The Raspberry Pi computer is a family of computers that was

00:01:04.099 --> 00:01:13.059
first launched in 2012, so about 10 years old now. They're created by an organisation

00:01:13.059 --> 00:01:21.500
here in the UK called the Raspberry Pi Foundation. The foundation's aim is really to improve

00:01:21.500 --> 00:01:26.620
outcomes for folks through computer science and education and things like that. And the

00:01:26.620 --> 00:01:33.620
way that they do that is they create a very, very low cost computer. They started out with

00:01:33.620 --> 00:01:38.739
a computer that cost $35. It's about the size of a deck of cards. And then there've been

00:01:38.739 --> 00:01:45.540
multiple iterations of that over the years. And then at some point they released a smaller

00:01:45.540 --> 00:01:52.580
version of that computer, which only cost $15. So now there are probably three main

00:01:52.580 --> 00:01:58.980
members of the Raspberry Pi family. We'll take a look at those in a little more detail.

00:01:58.980 --> 00:02:04.860
The Raspberry Pi 4 Model B is the most common of the Raspberry Pi family at the moment.

00:02:04.860 --> 00:02:12.419
It's the newest kind of standard size version of the computer. This particular one is in

00:02:12.419 --> 00:02:17.339
a nice rainbow case, but the computer itself, you can see how small it is. It's probably

00:02:17.339 --> 00:02:25.179
roughly the size of a deck of cards, something like that. They start at $35. That's the 1GB

00:02:25.179 --> 00:02:34.179
model. They go all the way up to 8GB of RAM. It's a 4-core CPU at 1.5GHz. There's an SD

00:02:34.179 --> 00:02:39.979
card slot underneath for storage and all the things you would expect from a modern

00:02:39.979 --> 00:02:47.539
computer. So USB 3.0, Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, HDMI out, that kind of thing.

00:02:47.539 --> 00:02:56.460
Next we have the Raspberry Pi Zero 2W. This is the second iteration of the Zero size computer.

00:02:56.460 --> 00:03:02.820
You can see that that one is just over an inch wide, a little larger than a stick of

00:03:02.860 --> 00:03:11.860
gum, I guess. These are the $15 computers. So it has a 4-core CPU at 1GHz, 512MB of RAM,

00:03:11.860 --> 00:03:21.500
Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, HDMI out, and again, the SD card for the operating system.

00:03:21.500 --> 00:03:27.740
Then finally, we have the largest of the Raspberry Pi computers, but that's only because it's

00:03:27.740 --> 00:03:33.740
built inside this keyboard here. So you can see the keyboard has similar slots to the

00:03:33.740 --> 00:03:41.059
Raspberry Pi 4. It's basically a Raspberry Pi 4 inside a keyboard case.

00:03:41.059 --> 00:03:47.020
It's important to remember that the Raspberry Pi is just a computer. It's a small Linux

00:03:47.020 --> 00:03:54.139
computer, and as such, works very similarly to most other computers, particularly computers

00:03:54.139 --> 00:03:59.059
using the Linux operating system.

00:03:59.059 --> 00:04:03.580
So what about the R4Pi project? What is it, and what does it do?

00:04:03.580 --> 00:04:12.300
So the R4Pi project provides pre-built binaries of the R language, first of all, but also

00:04:12.300 --> 00:04:23.619
provides a CRAN-like repository where we make available pre-compiled versions of CRAN packages.

00:04:23.619 --> 00:04:30.100
Now, we don't do all of CRAN, maybe one day. Right now, we're just doing a subset of CRAN.

00:04:30.100 --> 00:04:35.899
So we're building somewhere in the region of 250, maybe 300 packages, something like that

00:04:35.899 --> 00:04:39.980
at the moment, but we're adding more all the time.

00:04:39.980 --> 00:04:48.260
The way that this benefits users is that if you're unaware, if you're a Linux user and

00:04:48.260 --> 00:04:53.220
you use CRAN, CRAN gives you the source code rather than a pre-compiled binary like they

00:04:53.220 --> 00:05:00.019
do for Windows and Mac. This is great because R knows how to build them and things like

00:05:00.019 --> 00:05:04.660
that, but it can be very time-consuming. There are often dependencies which aren't necessarily

00:05:04.660 --> 00:05:11.619
met in your build environment, and so the R4Pi project builds those packages for you

00:05:11.619 --> 00:05:17.260
and then makes them available. In this regard, it's very similar to RStudio's package manager,

00:05:17.260 --> 00:05:21.420
but obviously on a much smaller scale.

00:05:21.420 --> 00:05:26.459
With those packages available, it becomes much easier for R users on the Raspberry Pi

00:05:26.459 --> 00:05:32.260
to install those packages. The installation is much quicker and there's no build that

00:05:32.260 --> 00:05:37.500
needs to occur. And from there, people can get started much more quickly with R itself

00:05:37.500 --> 00:05:41.420
without having to worry about all of this build stuff.

00:05:41.420 --> 00:05:48.420
Okay, so let's take a look at a couple of examples. In this first one, I'm going to

00:05:48.420 --> 00:05:56.540
log in to the Raspberry Pi via SSH from an iPad. So this is my little kind of desktop

00:05:56.540 --> 00:06:04.179
iPad setup that I've got going on. I'm going to use a program called blink to SSH into

00:06:04.179 --> 00:06:10.260
the Raspberry Pi. This basically gets me a kind of Linux terminal, but on the iPad, a

00:06:10.260 --> 00:06:17.859
butterfly flew into my office and I've typed the password wrong as a result. Okay, so we're

00:06:17.859 --> 00:06:26.100
logged in and we're going to run R. It looks exactly like R does everywhere else. What

00:06:26.100 --> 00:06:29.739
we can do though is if we look at options repo, so if we look at the repository that's

00:06:29.739 --> 00:06:36.940
set, our kind of default CRAN is actually packages.r4pi.org, which is the CRAN-like

00:06:36.940 --> 00:06:44.299
repository that we maintain as part of the R4Pi project. So that repository contains

00:06:44.299 --> 00:06:53.739
the pre-built binary packages that we've talked about, and when you install them, it

00:06:53.739 --> 00:06:57.380
does what R usually does, which is ask you if you want to create a personal library if

00:06:57.380 --> 00:07:05.859
you haven't already done so. Then it will download those packages from R4Pi.org. Download

00:07:05.859 --> 00:07:18.779
will take a moment, so we might just speed through that a little bit. Then once the

00:07:18.779 --> 00:07:25.820
packages are downloaded, you'll see that it says installing binary package curl and installing

00:07:25.820 --> 00:07:33.660
binary package rcpp and so on. This is different to what would happen if you installed those

00:07:33.660 --> 00:07:37.059
packages from CRAN. If you installed them from CRAN, it would say installing source

00:07:37.059 --> 00:07:44.420
package curl and so on, and it would try and compile those packages on the Raspberry Pi,

00:07:44.420 --> 00:07:51.339
which can be a very time-consuming process. Obviously, there are occasionally build dependencies

00:07:51.339 --> 00:07:58.100
and things like that, which we've taken care of for you with the R4Pi project. This makes

00:07:58.100 --> 00:08:04.380
installation a lot faster, and then once the packages are installed, you can load them

00:08:04.380 --> 00:08:10.980
as you would normally. In this example, you see the Raspberry Pi desktop, so this would

00:08:10.980 --> 00:08:15.299
be particularly useful if you're using one of the larger Raspberry Pis, Raspberry Pi

00:08:15.299 --> 00:08:21.579
4, Raspberry Pi 400. We're actually going to do some work inside an IDE. In this case,

00:08:21.579 --> 00:08:29.459
we're using Visual Studio Code, which is available in the default Raspberry Pi repositories.

00:08:29.459 --> 00:08:35.419
Once that's fully loaded, you'll see that we have the R extension installed, and that

00:08:35.419 --> 00:08:41.820
the R extension makes it possible for us to do things like run individual chunks in this

00:08:41.820 --> 00:08:48.539
R Markdown document, for instance. In this case, it's just running that chunk now, and

00:08:48.619 --> 00:08:56.460
you'll see that the results come up in a window on the side, in a pane on the side, I guess.

00:08:56.460 --> 00:09:01.099
And you can knit the whole document from here as well, so just hit the knit button, it's

00:09:01.099 --> 00:09:08.020
knitting the example, and then once that's knitted, we can go and take a look at it.

00:09:08.020 --> 00:09:13.020
And it looks exactly as you would expect it to. It's a very basic R Markdown document,

00:09:13.020 --> 00:09:19.380
obviously, but hopefully proves the point.

00:09:19.380 --> 00:09:25.659
Then we can also flip over to this slightly more complex example. This is a really, really

00:09:25.659 --> 00:09:35.419
nice ggplot2 plot example that I've borrowed from the Palmer Penguins package website.

00:09:35.419 --> 00:09:42.619
And if we just step through that with control and return, as you would normally, step through,

00:09:42.619 --> 00:09:51.419
and then when we go for the last step, it will print the plot in the window on the side.

00:09:51.419 --> 00:09:58.619
We're quite zoomed in here for display purposes, but as you can see, when we actually look

00:09:58.619 --> 00:10:03.059
at the plot in more detail, it looks exactly as you would expect it to look.

00:10:03.059 --> 00:10:10.140
Okay, in this last example, we're going to take a look at a Shiny application. So this

00:10:10.140 --> 00:10:17.580
is the Shiny application, fairly standard stuff. And we're going to run that directly

00:10:17.580 --> 00:10:25.580
from the terminal on the Raspberry Pi. So to do that, we use the Shiny's built-in function,

00:10:25.580 --> 00:10:32.500
which is just run app, so shiny double colon run app. And then when we hit return on there,

00:10:32.500 --> 00:10:38.059
the application will start. Now this is only listening locally at the moment on a random

00:10:38.140 --> 00:10:45.099
port, but if we go into the Raspberry Pi's web browser, we can take a look at what that

00:10:45.099 --> 00:10:55.419
application looks like. So we put in local host, port number, and there it is. So it's a

00:10:55.419 --> 00:11:00.539
BASTA fusion model visualization. The application is not hugely important.

00:11:00.539 --> 00:11:07.900
The point here, as much as anything, is that the R4Pi project enables you to do the things

00:11:07.900 --> 00:11:15.900
that you can do everywhere else, simply and easily on the Raspberry Pi as well. So it's a

00:11:16.700 --> 00:11:21.419
standard kind of application. There are some inputs which you can manipulate, which change

00:11:21.419 --> 00:11:29.419
the outputs a little bit. And that works exactly as you would expect. But what if

00:11:30.460 --> 00:11:35.739
you want to run that persistently? You want to run that, say, on your home network?

00:11:37.900 --> 00:11:43.340
Well, the Raspberry Pi can help with that as well. Because of the Raspberry Pi's low power

00:11:43.340 --> 00:11:51.340
draw requirements, they make ideal servers to run kind of 24-7. So the way that we would do that

00:11:51.340 --> 00:11:59.739
for a Shiny application is we would switch back to the terminal. We would drop out of the

00:12:01.099 --> 00:12:06.859
running Shiny application here, so we'll stop that. And then we'll run it again, but this time

00:12:06.859 --> 00:12:14.140
with a couple of extra parameters. So we're going to set the host to 0.0.0.0. That's basically just

00:12:14.140 --> 00:12:18.299
a way of telling it to listen on the network rather than just locally.

00:12:18.299 --> 00:12:23.099
And then we'll set a port so that it's easier for me to find later on.

00:12:25.659 --> 00:12:31.820
Once that's up and running, we can test it. We can test to make sure that that's available

00:12:31.820 --> 00:12:36.460
on the network. So to do that, I'm going to flip over to my iPad.

00:12:40.059 --> 00:12:46.940
And then once on the iPad, I'm going to type in the IP address or the host name, if I have one,

00:12:46.940 --> 00:12:50.619
of the machine on the local network. I'm using the IP address here.

00:12:52.059 --> 00:12:55.340
And then I'm going to put in the port that we specified earlier on.

00:12:56.219 --> 00:13:03.099
And we'll see if that loads. And there we go. It's the exact same BASTAfusion model visualization

00:13:04.140 --> 00:13:10.700
running in the exact same way as before. The rendering is probably a little different

00:13:10.700 --> 00:13:15.900
because we're using the iPad web browser rather than the one that's built into the Raspberry Pi.

00:13:16.940 --> 00:13:21.820
But other than that, it works in exactly the same way. The same inputs connected to the same

00:13:22.780 --> 00:13:26.780
outputs that change the plots in exactly the same way.

00:13:34.299 --> 00:13:39.500
One of the things that I'm most excited about about running R on a Raspberry Pi

00:13:39.500 --> 00:13:45.820
is because it's a very small computer, you can run them in places where you wouldn't

00:13:45.820 --> 00:13:54.140
normally run a $1,000, $2,000 computer. They can be powered by batteries in a lot of cases,

00:13:54.140 --> 00:14:00.940
especially the smaller ones. You can run those from a USB battery bank. But you can imagine

00:14:02.460 --> 00:14:07.500
ordinarily with data science, people give us data. So the data is collected somewhere.

00:14:08.059 --> 00:14:13.020
It's bundled together, often not very well, and then handed over to the data scientists

00:14:13.020 --> 00:14:19.900
for analysis. But what we can do when we have a small computer like the Raspberry Pi,

00:14:19.900 --> 00:14:25.500
is we can put that computer where the data is collected. So that could be the data collection

00:14:25.500 --> 00:14:31.900
device as well as the place where the analysis occurs. This kind of concept in computing is

00:14:31.900 --> 00:14:39.179
often referred to as edge computing because you can take the centralized resources that are often

00:14:39.179 --> 00:14:44.460
used for this sort of work and you can move them to the edge of the network. This means that you

00:14:44.460 --> 00:14:49.739
can run projects in a lot more interesting places than you might otherwise be able to.

00:14:52.140 --> 00:14:57.580
Because of the low power requirements of the Raspberry Pi, you can run them in a car while

00:14:57.580 --> 00:15:03.340
you're out power sending. I can imagine people running them while they're, you know, on a

00:15:03.340 --> 00:15:11.340
building site or in a digger. Maybe even a farmer looking after cows in a field,

00:15:13.020 --> 00:15:21.659
in a forest, on a boat. The possibilities really are endless with such a small low power device.

00:15:23.580 --> 00:15:28.859
There are many different ways that you could run the types of projects that we've talked about

00:15:29.659 --> 00:15:33.260
here today. You don't need a Raspberry Pi computer to do any of this stuff.

00:15:34.299 --> 00:15:42.700
But for me, the kind of low cost, the kind of ease of entry into the ecosystem

00:15:43.260 --> 00:15:48.380
is a really big boon for a certain class of users. Whether they're people who are just, you

00:15:48.380 --> 00:15:53.900
know, coming to R for the first time, just want to learn. People want to learn Linux so that they can

00:15:53.900 --> 00:16:00.940
use R on Linux. Because obviously that's more or less a de facto operating system for scientific

00:16:00.940 --> 00:16:08.380
and technical computing at this point. Or for any other reason. Just having something that's very

00:16:08.380 --> 00:16:19.179
low cost and very accessible for folks is a really nice way to help people get into the R ecosystem.

00:16:20.059 --> 00:16:26.539
Thanks for watching the talk to this point. Please check out the r4pi.org website,

00:16:26.539 --> 00:16:30.140
check out the Raspberry Pi family of computers if that's something that you think you might be

00:16:30.140 --> 00:16:37.979
interested in. My personal website and Twitter details are there as well if you want them.

00:16:37.979 --> 00:16:44.460
Thanks again and I hope you have an excellent rest of the conference. Bye.

00:16:49.179 --> 00:16:49.919
Bye.

